subject: test treewide: iwyu
commitMessage:
test treewide: iwyu

These changes are done by running iwyu manually under clang14.

Suppressed some obvious impl or details headers. Kept the recommended
public headers.

IWYU can increase readability, make maintenance easier, and avoid errors
in some cases. See details in
https://github.com/include-what-you-use/include-what-you-use/blob/master/docs/WhyIWYU.md.

This commit also uses its best effort to correct obvious errors through
iwyu pragma.
See reference here:
https://github.com/include-what-you-use/include-what-you-use#how-to-correct-iwyu-mistakes

Tested: unit test passed.

Signed-off-by: Nan Zhou <nanzhoumails@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I983b6f75601707cbb0f2f04546c3362ff4ba7fee

Can you mention in your commit message what these do?

I suspect I can understand from the context, but getting some explicit docs on this might be good.

There are common things that it obviously gets wrong (like gtest).  I wonder if there's a way to avoid this boilerplate everywhere?  just thinking out loud.
Yes, I added a sentence for this. Unfortunately I don't know if there is better option besides pragma.
Aren't these already covered by gtest.h
Done. Yes, these headers don't make sense to me. I don't see them added in the internal version of iwyu.
So, should we look into that then?
Apologize, look into what? Why does iwyu include these two headers in our repo but not g3? What do you want me to do? Is creating an issue in iwyu enough?
We don't want to forward declare this I don't think?

I didn't dig into why iwyu thought this forward declaration is necessary. What's interesting is that it suggests removing "async_resp.hpp" and forward declaring AsyncResp.

For now, I used pragma to mute this.
There's lots of these includes that I'm not understanding why IWYU is suggesting them, but I don't really want to go through and document all of them.  Lets see if we can understand the "weird" ones.
For things like gtest, that are used across the project, does iwyu have a way to avoid having all the boilerplate spread throughout the project?

It provides an option to fix it in the headers that sources include, https://github.com/include-what-you-use/include-what-you-use/blob/master/docs/IWYUPragmas.md#iwyu-pragma-private.

I am not aware of other options. See https://github.com/include-what-you-use/include-what-you-use#how-to-correct-iwyu-mistakes
I prefer just using IWYU pragma. Done.

My suggestion used IWYU pragma, so I don't quite understand your answer.  I'm suggesting that we shouldn't include headers that the test harness documentation itself (gtest in this case) doesn't recommend.

> I'm suggesting that we shouldn't include headers that the test harness documentation itself (gtest in this case) doesn't recommend.

That's what we do now, right? 

> I prefer just using IWYU pragma. Done.

This is for 

```
#include <gtest/gtest.h> // IWYU pragma: keep


// IWYU pragma: no_include <gtest/gtest-message.h>
// IWYU pragma: no_include <gtest/gtest-test-part.h>

on these?

Or maybe we should define a gtest_local.h to avoid the boilerplate?
```

I was saying I went with the first option.
why quotes here instead of <
iwyu uses quotes.
but the line below it uses <, so maybe iwyu is inconsistent?  Could this be made to be <  ?

I made "gtest/gtest_pred_impl.h" consistent to "" which is what iwyu includes.

I don't know why it's "" in the first place.
Should we figure out why before we check this in?
No, I didn't look into why it includes "gtest/gtest_pred_impl.h". Is that blocking us getting this clean up in?
?  This doesn't seem like something we should include directly?  I don't use any allocator traits below?
same to the other thread. Do we need a reason for each header?

No, we don't need a reason for each header, but we generally shouldn't be including gcc specific headers, because the coding standard says to avoid implementation specific headers, so I'd like to at least understand it.  I suspect this is a case where we need another pragma.

https://github.com/include-what-you-use/include-what-you-use/issues/166

I have muted it.
Any idea what these are used for?  I didn't think we had any direct sd-bus usage that we need to include (we don't list an sd-bus dependency directly).
iwyu will provide an explanation though, I didn't actually check every header it includes. Do we need to worry about including these extra header?

Yes, we do, because in the ideal case, we should be entirely using sdbusplus abstractions, and shouldn't be using sd-bus.h directly.  I don't see any sd-bus.h usages in this file, that's why I question it.

As stated in the commit message IWYU has false positives, and to my eye, this looks like one of them.  I could be wrong, but if it's just a matter of rerunning the results, it would be good to know.

sd-bus.h:
sd_bus_error

sd-bus-protocol.h:
SD_BUS_TYPE_ARRAY, SD_BUS_TYPE_VARIANT, SD_BUS_TYPE_STRUCT, SD_BUS_TYPE_DICT_ENTRY

Ack

I didn't realize we used those types directly in here, but I guess we did.
I think we can remove this now that we're using the more specific includes.
Done
This is another one I don't understand.  We don't use type_index?

I suspect this is implicitly used when you compare to boost objects
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/55138/5/include/openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp#501
But if it's used within the boost object..... the boost object should be the thing #including it, not us, right?

../include/openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp should add these lines:
#include <boost/type_index/type_index_facade.hpp>     // for operator==

Briefly reading from https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_79_0/doc/html/boost_typeindex_header_reference.html#header.boost.type_index.type_index_facade_hpp, seems to me it's valid to include this header and it's private. I also didn't find an issue about this header in iwyu.

I kept it. Please reopen if this doesn't make sense.

operator== in what namespace?  I'd like to understand this before this checks in.  If we don't understand the changes being made, we won't be able to enforce that they're correct on future code reviews, thats why this is important.

in boost namespace I believe. Is this a false positive?

I understand why this is important.
I believe it's another false positive.
Done
Nothing in the below throws exceptions.

I assume it is the try catch blocks
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/55138/5/include/openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp#279

The the catch blocks can be deleted, because findRemainingObjectsForEnumerate does not throw.

> The the catch blocks can be deleted, because findRemainingObjectsForEnumerate does not throw.

It actually can, and if you remove the try catch blocks, clang-tidy-bugprone-exception-escape will fail.  I've never been able to figure out why it throws, because you're right, the code doesn't look like it should.

> I assume it is the try catch blocks

Try catch blocks are part of the language, they shouldn't need to #include <exception> to use.

https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/header/exception

That's everything in <exception>, and it's possible i missed something, but nothing from that file looks like its in here?

IWYU said

```
../include/openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp should add these lines:
#include <exception>                                  // for exception
```

But there's no exception reference. This seems to me yet another false positive.

Muted for now.

> the code doesn't look like it should. (throw)

It used std::visit, and std::visit can throw a variant (std::bad_variant_access)

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/4e23a444e8503fd03ab40de2844c783e142ebef8/include/openbmc_dbus_rest.hpp#L167
Right, but in that case I would expect it to ask us to #include <variant> not <exception>

I agree. It throws a variant type. I was responding to your 
>  I've never been able to figure out why it throws, because you're right, the code doesn't look like it should.
Gotcha.   that damn valueless_by_exception thing again..... I wonder how we can fix that.  Good catch.
For things like gtest, that are used across the project, does iwyu have a way to avoid having all the boilerplate spread throughout the project?
As discussed in the other thread. IWYU pragma is the way that IWYU suggests to correct wrong includes.

Most comments are around specific headers, please let me know your preference, I can probably provide the reason why iwyu suggests certain headers, but just to confirm before I actually do that, since it takes time.

I don't want you to document every header.  Most of them look correct;  I've tried to only call out the headers that don't look correct, are adding a lot of repeated boilerplate or are disobeying the coding standard.
Done. Replied all comments.

In the patch stackup you have here, would it make sense to put the iwyu patch last in the series?  I think the other 3 can merge if that's done, so that gives us time to round up the last few of these.
Let me try.
Split.
